	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>High global beef prices and the functioning of the EU beef supply chain</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC decision to establish a ‘special working group to focus on the needs of the beef sector’ has been welcomed by farmers and parliamentarians across Europe. According to press reports, ‘the group will investigate the need for adapting market instruments to help increase profit margins within the beef sector, but also to control the volatility within profit margins.’ A key focus is likely to be the relationship between producers and retailers, particularly regarding the distribution of costs in meeting EU and retailer production standards. The working group will focus on the internal market and will not have a mandate to review the trade negotiations with Mercosur.</p><p>In the beef sector the impact of high feed costs has been compounded by the dry weather conditions in northern Europe in the first half of 2011. Currently the EC is exploring the option of advancing disbursement of direct aid payments to ease the cash flow problems of EU cattle farmers.</p><p>At the global level meanwhile, ‘world beef prices look set to stay high’, given increased production costs in Brazil and the appreciation of the Brazilian real (+9% against the euro in the last year). According to analysts, production costs in Brazil since 2008 have risen ‘above those of Australia in US dollar terms’. This situation is exacerbated by the profitability of double cropping corn and soya, driving beef farming in Brazil to remoter regions that face higher transport costs.</p><p>As a consequence of these developments, Brazilian beef exports in the first quarter of 2011 fell 14% compared to the same period in 2010.</p><p>According to Rabobank analysts, the ‘days of cheap and widely available Brazilian beef appear to be over’, and ‘Brazilian cattle prices are likely to remain at above historical levels.’ They argue that ‘as demand for meat in developing markets continues to rise, and demand in developed markets recovers, the world will need to pay higher prices to stimulate global beef supply.’</p><p>Meanwhile high global beef prices have opened up new export opportunities for some ACP beef exporters. At the beginning of 2011 the state-owned Kenya Meat Commission (KMC) signed a contract to supply 1,000 tonnes of beef per month to Iran, with scope for expanding exports depending on the level of demand. This comes on top of a reported 3,000 tonnes of Kenyan beef exports to Qatar and the United Arab Emirates. KMC is also reported to be eying Egypt and Saudi Arabia as potential markets.</p><p>The Kenyan private meat processor ‘Farmers’ Choice’ is also exploring export markets, following investment in halal facilities by the Aga Khan Fund for Economic Development and a Norwegian government-owned development finance company.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
