<a href="http://www.farminglife.com/news/ciolos_recognises_pain_in_beef_sector_1_2748036" target="_self">http://www.farminglife.com/news/ciolos_recognises_pain_in_beef_sector_1_...</a></p><p><i>TheBeefSite.com</i>, ‘Drought difficulties in Europe’, 9 June 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thebeefsite.com/news/34784/drought-difficulties-in-europe" target="_self">http://www.thebeefsite.com/news/34784/drought-difficulties-in-europe</a></p><p><i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Rising Brazil ranch costs to keep beef prices high’, 8 June 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/rising-brazil-ranch-costs-to-keep-beef-prices-high--3231.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/rising-brazil-ranch-costs-to-keep-beef-pri...</a></p><p><i>Business Daily</i>, ‘Kenya signs lucrative meat supply deal with Iran’, 19 January 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya+signs+lucrative+meat+supply+deal+with+Iran/-/539552/1091800/-/item/0/-/mi96l3z/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Kenya+signs+lucrative+meat+supply+dea...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The extension to the EU beef sector of the EC’s policy work to strengthen the functioning of supply chains can be seen as a natural extension of previous EC work on the functioning of milk supply chains. ACP beef exporters are likely to take a particular interest in any findings of the new EU working group as regards the management of relations between producers and retailers, particularly in terms of the distribution of costs associated with meeting EU and retailer production standards.</p><p>However, moves to develop work on the functioning of beef supply chains in the EU are also indicative of the wider relevance of this approach in an era of heightened global price volatility. Increased dialogue between the EC and ACP governments on the appropriate application of policies to strengthen the functioning of agricultural supply chains potentially offers an important policy response to the problems of global price volatility, compounded by exchange rate volatility, that are facing ACP governments. </p><p>With rising global beef prices and reduced exports from Brazil, opportunities for ACP beef exporters to develop new export markets beyond the EU are emerging. This is in part linked to the less stringent food-safety and production-process-related requirements on these markets. It is however also related to the different structure of demand in these markets compared to the EU market (where demand for lower quality beef cuts is declining). For some ACP beef producers, the high global prices could offer a window of opportunity for establishing and consolidating their position in rapidly growing developing country markets.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
